<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-320-314  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 320 314.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Computerworld  April 9 1990 v24 n15 p72(2).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Once you're in, the water is fine. (computer-aided softwareengineering at American Electric Power Service Corp.)(FirstPerson) (column)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Kalisch, Richard A.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>American Electric Power Service Corp, a $5 billion electricutility holding company in Columbus, OH, decided in 1988 to investin computer-aided software engineering to speed modernization ofits antiquated core business systems.andP;  Update requirements piledup faster than developers could handle with traditional tools, andmanagement continually proposed new systems.andP;  Cobol and CICSprogramming produced inconsistent results, and fourth-generationlanguages tended to produce equally poor code.andP;  The firmdetermined from these experiences that it needed a comprehensive,integrated product that would support a specific methodology andgenerate third-generation code from design specifications.andO;American Electric now uses Andersen Consulting's Foundationproduct, which addresses the entire software life cycle.andP;  Thecompany estimates CASE tools have reduced coding time by 50percent.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Company:   American Electric Power Service Corp. (automation).andO;Topic:     Computer-aided software engineeringProgram Development ToolsProgram Development TechniquesCase Study.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>